President Obama held a meeting with his national security and public health teams to discuss Ebola preparedness at home and the efforts to contain the epidemic in West Africa. The Department of Health and Human Services is leading the effort to ensure hospitals and the health system are prepared to identify and isolate Ebola cases. The President was also updated on the measures in place to screen individuals traveling from affected West African countries and the monitoring requirements upon arrival in the United States. The meeting emphasized the need to aggressively tackle the challenge in West Africa and coordinate with healthcare workers on the frontlines. The President highlighted that containing the epidemic in West Africa is crucial to prevent additional cases domestically. The meeting included various government officials such as the Vice President, Secretary of Defense, Secretary of Health and Human Services, Secretary of Homeland Security, and the Ebola Response Coordinator.